            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "For Simone Reyes, the rhythmic rumble of a MUNI bus is the sound of progress. Raised in a working-class Oakland neighborhood, she learned early on how transportation dictates opportunity. Her father, a port worker, and her mother, a Dominican immigrant who worked as a home health aide, relied on a frequently delayed bus system. Simone vividly remembers her father missing her middle school science fair award ceremony, stuck for an hour on a broken-down bus\u2014a quiet injustice that planted the seed for her future career.\n\nDriven and studious, Simone excelled academically, earning a scholarship to UC Davis and later pursuing her Master's in Urban and Regional Planning at UC Berkeley. It was there she found her calling: using data and design to create equitable transit systems. San Francisco, with its dense, complex urban fabric, was the ultimate challenge. She started as a junior analyst at the SFMTA and, over a decade, proved herself a visionary, becoming a Senior Transportation Planner who champions community-first infrastructure.\n\nA key turning point was her successful campaign for a protected bike lane and bus-only corridor in a neighborhood previously disconnected from the city's core. Seeing residents use it daily affirmed her belief that her work wasn't just about traffic flow, but about social mobility. Today, Simone lives in a small, tidy apartment in Hayes Valley. Her 3.8-mile MUNI commute is a daily field study. She knows the drivers on her line by name and mentally redesigns intersections as she passes them.\n\nHer social life revolves around a tight-knit group of friends, fellow professionals she met in grad school. They gather weekly for dinner, debating city politics and sharing career triumphs. While her demanding job leaves little time for serious dating, she finds fulfillment in her work and community. Simone\u2019s dream is to one day lead the development of a major new transit line, connecting the city's most isolated communities. She is helping to build the San Francisco she always believed was possible\u2014one where no one has to miss their child\u2019s big moment because the bus was late."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.  (Age 12) She remembers the squeak of the empty plastic chair next to her mother in the school gymnasium. Her volcano model, which had felt like a triumph, now seemed small and silly. The pride she\u2019d saved up for her father dissolved into a quiet, hollow ache. It wasn't anger at him, but at the unseen force\u2014the broken-down bus\u2014that had stolen the moment. That night, she first understood that a late bus wasn't an inconvenience; it was a quiet injustice, a thief of shared joy.\n\n2.  (Grad School at UC Berkeley) A guest lecturer projected a map of Oakland overlaid with freeways, calling them \"concrete scars\" that severed communities of color. The academic term ignited a personal memory: the constant rumble of the freeway from her childhood window. Suddenly, her family\u2019s struggles weren\u2019t just bad luck; they were a design. In that dark lecture hall, a cold fury settled in her, hardening into purpose. She wouldn't just study the systems; she would learn how to dismantle and rebuild them, equitably.\n\n3.  (Three Years Ago) Weeks after her bus-only corridor went live, she stood on a corner with coffee, just watching. An express bus, full of commuters, sailed past unimpeded. A mother, toddler in a bike seat, pedaled smoothly in the new protected lane. No one knew who Simone was. A profound, anonymous satisfaction washed over her. This wasn't a data point on a chart; this was a neighborhood breathing easier. It was the quiet, tangible proof that her abstract plans created real-world mobility and safety.\n\n4.  (Last Year) Her regular MUNI driver, Maria, once held the bus for her as she sprinted, breathless, to the stop. \"I see you every morning, mija,\" Maria had said with a warm smile. \"Planners gotta get to work on time, too.\" The small kindness and recognition struck Simone deeply. It humanized the entire system for her in a new way. It wasn't just about routes and schedules, but about the network of people who depended on it\u2014and on each other\u2014to keep the city moving.\n\n5.  (Last Month) At her weekly dinner, her friends debated city politics while Simone found herself sketching a hypothetical light rail extension on a napkin. Her friend Maya peered over her shoulder and teased, \"You never turn it off, do you?\" Simone just smiled. For her, this wasn't work; it was hope. Sharing that napkin blueprint with people who understood her vision felt more intimate and fulfilling than any romance. It reaffirmed that her purpose and her community were inextricably linked."
